{"headline": "Advice on Addiction in Boomers", "body": "\nAsk an Expert this week features  \n, who will field questions about baby boomers and addiction.         \n\nAccording to the Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration, use of illegal substances is increasing in adults over 50. Abuse of alcohol and prescription drugs has also been on the rise. With the population of adults over 65 expected to grow to 73 million from 40 million between 2010 and 2030,  \n stands to overwhelm the country\u2019s mental health care system, according to a recent report by the Institute of Medicine.         \n\nDr. Krantz will offer advice to boomers and families of boomers on when and how to seek help. Dr. Krantz is the medical director and the director of medical research at the  \n in West Palm Beach, Fla., a nonprofit addiction recovery center based on the 12-step principles of Alcoholics Anonymous. She was instrumental in founding the Boomer Program at Hanley in 2009 after identifying the needs of this demographic. She has a long history in addiction medicine.         \n\nDr. Krantz helps train addiction medicine doctors through the University of Florida. She is also collaborating in a study with Scripps Florida on potential new addiction treatments. Dr. Krantz is also researching the use of neuro-imaging in the study of addiction.         \n\nDr. Krantz earned her medical degree at the Des Moines University College of Osteopathic Medicine and completed a family practice residency at Jackson Memorial Hospital in Miami. In 2010, Dr. Krantz became a fellow of the American Society of Addiction Medicine. She was awarded the Heroes in Medicine award from the Palm Beach County Medical Society in 2008.         \n\nHere are examples of questions that Dr. Krantz is prepared to answer:         \n\n1. What are some of the signs and symptoms of addiction in boomers?         \n\n2. Are you seeing any new trends related to addiction in boomers?         \n\n3. What are some approaches to treating addiction in boomers?         \n\n4. Can you offer helpful ways to approach loved ones if you think they have an issue with alcohol or drugs?         \n\n \n        ", "url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/14/booming/advice-on-addiction-in-boomers.html", "date": "2013-08-14", "description": "Dr. Barbara Krantz will take questions on addictions of baby boomers, including when and how to seek help."}